## Faces

It may come to a surprise, if you weren't curious enough to interact with the mascot, but there are actually two versions of the cloud.

Let's start with the more stern character, the one which certainly did not escape your gaze.

Two circles on either side make up the eyes.

```html
<g fill="#acacfa">
	<g transform="translate(10 -2.5)">
		<circle r="2.5" />
	</g>
	<g transform="translate(-10 -2.5)">
		<circle r="2.5" />
	</g>
</g>
```

---

I like to position the shapes with group elements to change the origin of the coordinate system. It is slightly technical, so you are welcome to skip the note, but if you were to rely on the `cx` and `cy` attribute.

```html
<circle cx="10" cy="-2.5" r="2.5" />
```

If you were to apply a transformation, like a change in scale.

```html
<g transform="scale(0.5)">
	<circle cx="10" cy="-2.5" r="2.5" />
</g>
```

You would not scale the circle from its center, but from the point described by the group. You may want to, but in this instance I care to move the origin.

---

One horizontal line smack in the center is enough to introduce the mouth, and complete the unimpressed expression.

```html
<g fill="#acacfa" stroke="#acacfa" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round">
	<g transform="translate(0 8)">
		<path d="M -2 0 h 4" />
	</g>
</g>
```

<Center>
	<Face />
</Center>

Now, let's try to cheer things up with a few shapes. Add two ellipses below the eyes, two colorful cheeks.

```html
<g fill="#f9a3c6">
	<g transform="translate(10 2.5)">
		<ellipse rx="2.5" ry="1.4" />
	</g>
	<g transform="translate(-10 2.5)">
		<ellipse rx="2.5" ry="1.4" />
	</g>
</g>
```

Immediately after the horizontal line add a cheerful mug with a slightly more complex `<path>` element.

<!-- prettier-ignore -->
```html
<path d="M -2 0 h 4" /> 
<path d="M -2 0 v 2 a 2 2 0 0 0 4 0 v -2z" />
```

Why on top of the line? It'll make sense soon enough. Right now, let's enjoy the remarkable change brought by these small tweaks.

<Center>
	<Face trueColors={true} />
</Center>

## Interaction

As prefaced, you don't see the jolly face immediately. The plan is to show the somber character by default, and lift the mood only as the cursor enters the `<svg>` element. Time for Svelte to show its luster.

In the `<script>` tags import the `spring` function from the `svelte/motion` module.

```svelte
<script>
	import { spring } from 'svelte/motion';
</script>
```

Create an instance to describe a change scale, with an initial value of 0. You may already see where this is going.

```js
const scale = spring(0, {
	stiffness: 0.2,
	damping: 0.5
});
```

Use the value directly in the markup, to scale the shapes into oblivion. Hide the cheeks.

```svelte
<!-- both ellipses -->
<g transform="scale({$scale})">
	<ellipse rx="2.5" ry="1.4" />
</g>
```

Hide the expanded mouth, effectively returning to the first face.

```svelte
<g transform="scale({$scale})">
	<path d="M -2 0 v 2 a 2 2 0 0 0 4 0 v -2z" />
</g>
```

Not for long however. Define helper functions to change the spring's value: one to reach 1, and have the shapes return, one to move back to 0, and hide them back.

```js
const handleStart = () => {
	scale.set(1);
};

const handleEnd = () => {
	scale.set(0);
};
```

Call the functions following the `mouseenter` and `mouseleave` events respectively.

<!-- prettier-ignore -->
```svelte
<svg 
    on:mouseenter={handleStart} 
    on:mouseleave={handleEnd}>
	<!--  -->
</svg>
```

And reap the rewards.

